captions.text:
(Finebros) So, in this episode,
we're going to actually

be having you play 
a popular recent video game.
You think I can do it?
You guys know I suck at video games.

(Finebros) The game you're gonna play 
is called Five Nights at Freddy's.

(Finebros) You're a security guard
at a haunted Chuck E. Cheese,

like a haunted children's 
entertainment restaurant.

(Finebros) And you're supposed to try 
to stay alive for five straight nights

while the animatronic characters 
make their way to you

- and try to kill you.
- Okay.

(Finebros) So you'll have security cameras
that you'll be checking

- to see where they all are.
- Oh.

(Finebros) And then you have 
lights and doors

that you can shut 
if they come too close,

but every time you use 
the cameras, or shut the door,

or use your light, 
your battery power goes down.

So my only defense 
is to keep myself sheltered.

Family pizzeria looking 
for security guard to work
the night shift, 12 AM to 6 AM.

First night.
This is already scary.
Am I supposed to answer the phone?

(phone guy) ) Uh, I wanted to record 
a message for you,

to help you get settled 
in on your first night.

- Okay.
- (phone guy) So just be aware

that characters do 
tend to wander a bit.

They have some sort 
of free roaming mode at night.

(phone guy) But there's really 
nothing to worry about.

(phone guy) They'll probably try 
to forcefully stuff you

I don't want to get stuffed
into any suit.

(phone guy) It wouldn't be 
so bad if the suits themselves

weren't filled with cross beams, wires, 
and animatronic devices.
Does this guy ever stop talking?

Yeah, well, thanks a whole heap 
for telling me all this [bleep].

Uh-oh! Hey, hey.
Somebody's missing here.

All right, so I have to see
where these guys are.

There's that little guy.
He's in 1B.
I haven't seen nobody come at me yet.
I don't see that moving at all.

Oh, I see that I'm losing 
a lot of power just checking.

I don't like what 
that guy's talking about.

I'm too young to die 
so soon in the game!

- Is that a bad guy there?
- (Finebros) No, that's just a poster.
I'm down to half my power.

I'm running, rapidly running out 
of power and I haven't found

any of these guys 
and they're looking for me.
So I'm just sitting here, waiting to die.

There's still a few more places 
before he comes to me, right?
I'm just gonna shut the door.

- Close the door!
- He looks like a teddy bear.
Hah! All right, that felt good.

Ahhh, I'm down to 1% power.
Hit the lights.
Are they on top of me?
Can I go hide, like, under...

- I hear growling. Uh oh...
- (bell tolls)
I made it through the night?

Nobody got me.
I love it.

(phone guy) Well, if you're here 
listening, you made it to day two.

I'm sure you have 
everything under control.

- (door slams)
- There, I closed the door.

Light on, open the door.
Nobody there.
I can't get rid of this guy.

How can I call back 
that guy on the phone

and tell him to come 
change the light bulb?
So he must be coming close here.

He snuck up.
I almost had him.
I was gonna check that door.

So I can't hurt these guys,
just close the door.

Whoops, I have no power,
so now what?
I knew he was going to do that.
How much time do I have left?

(Finebros) So did you have fun 
playing the game?
You're tense and on your edge.
The fear factor didn't show up.

A game has to be something 
moving, something happening,

not just going around, 
looking and looking.

You guys thought it 
was gonna be terrifying.

- (Finebros) Did you find it scary?
- No.

A little creepy, 
a little haunted-housey.

Well, I knew something 
was gonna pop up,
I just didn't know it would startle me.

There is no process that scare you.
It's supposed to be a process,

something, not just move 
from one camera to another.

(Finebros) So a lot of people
love this game, but there's also been

a lot of people that think 
it's too simple of a game

and that it's not that complicated
and it's not that great.

- What do you think?
- I think it's silly.

I don't know how many 
times I'd find it fun.
It was kind of boring, sorta.

I think there's room 
for growth with this game.
I think it's a little simplistic.

You can't do nothing.
I mean, what?

What's the game?
Close the door?
I cannot shoot the guy and kill him.

(Finebros) Why do you think horror games
are some of the most popular games?

You know, there could be 
a good rush there.
I guess people like to get scared.

I mean, just like you pay money
to see scary movies, right?

It's a safe way to feel
in combat, and engaged,

and practice protecting oneself
and getting the monsters back.

(Finebros) Some people say that 
it is dangerous for people

of your age, health-wise, to play 
a game like Five Nights at Freddy's.
What do you think about that?

Oh, I know that I think 
it [inaudible] for nothing.

I'm insulted when they say people 
my age shouldn't play this game.
Give us a little more credit than that!

You know, we may be over 60,
but we're not in that diminished capacity.

(Finebros) So, last thing, the creator
of Five Nights at Freddy's

has made a sequel to the game,
which is a little more complex,

with different things 
you can do to survive.
Would you want to play the sequel?

I didn't enjoy that either,
so why should I enjoy the sequel?

(Finebros) Well, we're gonna 
have you play the sequel
Great, I gotta survive all five nights.
We live to play another day!

Thanks for watching 
this episode of Elders React.

You want to see us 
get scared some more?

Well, then subscribe 
to the React Channel.

We're gonna be doing the sequel,
whatever you call it, part two!
